  <div class="page-body">
    <div class="about-layout">

      <div class="about-body">
        <p class="dropcap">I came to software development in my 30s, after spending years working in digital media during the stretch when it was becoming something else. I work on the web applications team at Northeast Wisconsin Technical College, writing <strong>C# .NET</strong> and <strong>Salesforce Apex</strong>, building tools and public-facing applications for a technical college in Green Bay.</p>

        <div class="about-divider" aria-hidden="true">// music</div>

        <p>I make electronic music under the name <strong>Disaster Preparedness Club</strong>. The setup is all hardware — a Behringer TD-3, a handful of vintage synthesizers and drum machines. No DAW, no laptop on stage. Everything happens in real time on the machines. The name is accurate.</p>

        <div class="about-divider" aria-hidden="true">// hardware</div>

        <p>The Nature Oracle started as a question about what to do with a 1970s slide viewer. The CyGar cyberdeck started because I wanted a portable Linux machine that looked like I'd built it by hand. Both of them work. That's kind of the whole point.</p>

        <div class="about-divider" aria-hidden="true">// home lab</div>

        <p>I run a home lab on a rack in my office — <strong>Nextcloud</strong> for files, <strong>Pi-hole</strong> for DNS, <strong>Home Assistant</strong> for home automation. Things that came out of that lab show up in the projects. The rest of it is just infrastructure that doesn't call home.</p>
      </div>

